In a press briefing, White House Press Secretary Robert Gibbs addresses questions about the leaking of classified documents by WikiLeaks. He emphasizes that the release of these documents is a breach of federal law and poses potential harm to military operations and national security. Gibbs also discusses the relationship between the United States and Pakistan, stating that while there have been historical concerns about Pakistan's trustworthiness in the fight against terrorism, progress has been made in addressing safe havens and extremism in the country. He also addresses concerns about the ability of the government to protect confidential information and reiterates the administration's commitment to ensuring that BP fulfills its responsibilities in addressing the Gulf oil spill. Gibbs discusses the President's upcoming statements on the DISCLOSE Act and education, and briefly mentions the President's appearance on "The View" and a possible conversation about race.